    <b>Problem 1: </b>
        
        <script>
        console.log(typeof(true));
        console.log(typeof(3.4));
        console.log(typeof("Hello!"));
        console.log(typeof(Object()));
        console.log(typeof(console.log));
        console.log(typeof(undefined));
        
        </script>
    
    </br>
    A: Canonical Javascript types are boolean, number, string, object, functions, undefined.
    
</br>
</br>
    C: Unusal typeof() behavior: 
</br>
    Number: Both int and float are number. NaN is alsp a number. </br>
    Unicode: Unicode is identified as stirng.</br>
    Classes: Classes in javascript is just object.</br>
    Functions: Functions are special objeccts.</br>
    typeof(null) will incorrectly return as an object. Null is not an object.</br>
    Every object behaves like a dictionary.</br>
        
    </ul>
    </p>
        
    <p id="p2">
    <b>Problem 2:</b>
            </br>
                Type coercion means when Javascript tries to coerce one type into another to make two incompatible types compatible.
            </br>
                Two examples: </br>
                console.log(true + "false") gives truefalse; </br>
                console.log(3 + "2") gives 32.
            <script>
                console.log(true + "false");
                console.log(3 + "2");
            </script>
        </p>
    
    
    
    <p id="p3">
    <b>Prolem 3:</b>
    <script>
        function fact (n){
                    if (n < 0){
                        return undefined;
                    } 
                    if (n === 0){
                        return 1;
                    }
                    return n * fact(n - 1);
                }
        //test 
        console.log( fact(-2) ); 
        console.log( fact(0) ); 
        console.log( fact(1) ); 
        console.log( fact(5) ); 
        console.log( fact(12) );
    </script>
    </p>
    
    
